In any way, any extent or any degree.
examples: That isn't anything like a car.
She's not anything like as strong as me.

senses.sense: (derogatory, religion) A person who does not profess any particular creed; an indifferentist.
(religion) Beliefs and practices of an anythingarian.
plural of anything
At any time
"you're welcome" in response to "thank you" or "thanks."
Suitable for any time; not associated with any particular time.
(conjunctive) Regardless; anyhow.
examples: He didn't enjoy washing his car, but it was so dirty that he did it anyway.

senses.sense: Used to indicate that a statement explains or supports a previous statement. See anyhow and at least.
examples: I don't think that's true. I haven't found any evidence, anyway.

senses.sense: Used to indicate a change of subject.
Used at the end of a question for emphasis, or to direct the conversation to something of more broad importance (compare with more to the point).
(obsolete) In any way.
(rare) In any way or respect, at all.
(conjunctive, informal, chiefly North America, Philippines) Anyway, anyhow, in any case.
(rare, nonstandard) At any point in time.
(formal, now rare) From anywhere.
In or at any location.
examples: I don't know where I left my keys. They could be anywhere.
I'd rather be anywhere else.
For many 'home' is an affectation when used anywhere that 'house' would be appropriate, as in 'Home for Sale'.

senses.sense: To (in the direction of) any location.
examples: Anywhere you go in France, there will be bread and wine with dinner.
I'm staying home today. I'm not going anywhere.
Are you going anywhere special this weekend?

senses.sense: Any location or an unknown location.
examples: Anywhere is better than here!

senses.sense: The state or quality of being anywhere.
(US, nonstandard, slang or dialectal) anywhere
(rare) To (in the direction of) anywhere.
(colloquial, nonstandard) For any reason.
In any case.
Archaic form of anywhither.
